												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/andreaciman/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aciman-Andre-c-Jeannette-Montgomery-Barron-use-for-Roman-Year-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aciman-Andre-c-Jeannette-Montgomery-Barron-use-for-Roman-Year-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="André Aciman" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/andreaciman/">André Aciman</a></h6>
													André Aciman is the <em>New York Times</em> bestselling author of <em>Call Me By Your Name</em>, <em>Out of Egypt</em>, <em>Eight White Nights</em>, <em>False Papers</em>, <em>Alibis</em>, <em>Harvard Square</em>, <em>Enigma Variations</em>, and <em>Find Me</em>. He’s the editor of <em>The Proust Project</em> and teaches comparative literature at the Graduate Center of the City University of New York. He lives with his wife in Manhattan.																									</div>
											</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
										</div>

										<div class="after_content">

